        "id": 4290,
        "title": "Empowering Rwanda's agripreneurs: the Agribusiness Innovation and Incubation Hub(AIIH) at UNILAK and the case for women-specific cohorts",
        "slug": null,
        "image": "/uploads/media-1723135644630-585426771.jpeg",
        "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial;\">The YEAN Agribusiness Innovation and Incubation Hub (AIIH) at the University of Laic Adventist of Kigali (UNILAK), launched in 2023 with support from AIRTEA project,  successfully incubated its first cohort of 22 young entrepreneurs. The program, designed to nurture the next generation of Rwandan agripreneurs with a focus on climate-resilient agribusiness, provided a structured and learner cantered experience that included workshops, mentorship, networking opportunities, and access to essential resources. The program's emphasis on innovation, sustainability, and collaboration aimed to create a lasting positive impact on Rwanda's agricultural sector. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial;\">The AIIH program at UNILAK stands as a testament to the transformative power of empowering young people to lead the charge in agricultural innovation. The success stories emerging from the program underscore its effectiveness in nurturing entrepreneurial talent and fostering a vibrant agricultural ecosystem. However, the disparity in participation between male and female entrepreneurs highlights the need for targeted interventions to ensure greater inclusivity. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial;\">The underrepresentation of women in the first cohort, with only 7 out of 22 participants, signals the existence of barriers that prevent young women from fully engaging in such opportunities. These barriers may include societal expectations, limited access to resources, and a lack of confidence. Addressing these challenges necessitates a multi-faceted approach. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial;\">One potential solution is the establishment of women-specific cohorts within the AIIH program. This would create a safe and empowering space for young women to learn, collaborate, and grow together. It would also allow for tailored mentorship and support that addresses the unique challenges faced by women entrepreneurs in the agricultural sector. Additionally, targeted outreach and awareness campaigns can be implemented to encourage more young women to apply for the program and pursue their entrepreneurial aspirations. </span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 16px;font-family: Arial;\">YEAN as a gender sensitive enterprise, believes that promoting gender inclusivity and creating an environment where young women can thrive, its programs continuously unlock the full potential of Rwanda's entrepreneurial talent and contribute to a more equitable and prosperous agricultural sector. The success of the first cohort, despite the gender gap, demonstrates the program's effectiveness and highlights the immense potential for even greater impact with increased female participation. The AIIH program at UNILAK is not just an incubator for businesses; it is a catalyst for change, empowering young people to become leaders in sustainable agriculture and drive Rwanda's economic growth. </span></p>\r\n",
